3. Practical Examples

Here is how you would write the import lines depending on which file you are currently editing:
Scenario A: You are in App.jsx

You want to import your pages. Since App.jsx is inside src/, and the apps folder is also inside src/, you start with ./.

    Path: import OpacHome from './apps/opac/pages/OpacHome';

Scenario B: You are in OpacHome.jsx

You want to import a general Navbar from the components folder.

    You are inside pages/. You need to go back one to opac/. (../)

    You need to go back two to apps/. (../../)

    You need to go back three to src/. (../../../)

    Path: import Navbar from '../../../components/Navbar';

    Witty Tip: If you see ../../../../ in your code, your folders are getting a bit too deep! Try to keep your structure flat so you don't get "dot-fatigue."

4. How to verify the path

If you are using VS Code, here is the easiest way to never get a "Module Not Found" error again:

    Start typing import Test from '

    Press Ctrl + Space.

    VS Code will show you a dropdown list of folders. If you don't see apps, you are likely in the wrong starting folder (use ../ to go up until you see it).

5. Why ./apps/ might be confusing

Sometimes, developers use Absolute Paths or Aliases.
If you see someone import like this: import Home from '@/apps/Home', the @ is a shortcut for the src/ folder. Since you are just starting out with this Ubuntu/RPi setup, stick to the Relative Paths (./ and ../) for now so you can see exactly how the "tree" is connected.

